The extent to which “microscopic ecosystems engineers” contribute to the geomorphic process and importantly if they rely on the geomorphology to drive their existence is explored further in this paper.  Landscape processes in many drylands is driven by the interplay between fluvial and Aeolian processes \citep{mctainsh1987desert,bullard2003aeolian,field2009toward,langford1989fluvial}. citet{mctainsh1987desert} proposed a model of sediment recycling that provided an integrated interpretation of these processes in the landscape. Rivers feeding the internal draining river basin such as the Lake Chad and Lake Eyre transport vast amounts of fine sediments feeding the large dust source regions out of Africa, China and Australia. By linking river systems and wind erosion, McTainsh proposed looking at arid geomorphology as a system of sediment recycling operating on a massive scale. 

Sediment recycling results in a constantly changing soil surface. A conceptual model (Figure \ref{fig:dispersal-hazards}) highlights the interaction between the fluvial and aeolian systems. Floods supply fresh sediment to the claypan surface, having the effect of ‘re-zeroing’ the claypan surface, burying the effects of previous wind erosion activity. Once dry, however, time and climatic variation impact the sediment creating a mosaic of surface types. Source boarding sand dunes provide new sediments, larger, heavier particles that have the capacity to break down fine crusts as they bounce across the claypan. The ‘living soils’—the cyanobacteria crusts whilst known to be very responsive to changes in climatic stimulus, and therefore change the soil surface layer through time, have not generally been considered as a component of this fluvial - aeolian interaction. \footnote{need to develop model further}

