To increase understanding of the relationship of biocrusts to landscape stability we aimed to firstly gain basic knowledge about the microbial composition of different dryland soil types, and secondly to investigate the possible ecological strategies of microbes present. By understanding the ecology of communities and their constituent individual taxa, it should be possible to predict responses for various scenarios and devise interventions to manipulate the biotic component of geomorphic processes. Our main hypothesis is that wind differentially mobilises certain microbes from biocrusts, and that other microbes resist wind erosion. Related to this, we also expected to find biocrust organisms in watercourses. 

