Microbial composition of the dune flank, pan, and nebkha sites varied considerably as can be seen from Figure \ref{fig:nmds}. High abundance OTUs are likely to be important contributors to the overall community differences visualised in Figure \ref{fig:nmds}, and details of these can be found in Table \ref{tab:deseq3}. In fact many of the abundant OTUs were related to each other, meaning that community differences may be evident and easier to understand at higher taxonomic ranks as can be seen in Figures \ref{fig:waterp} and \ref{fig:waterc}. In summary of these results it is clear that \textit{Cyanobacteria} numerically dominate at the experimental sites (about 28 \% of bacterial sequences), the overall cyanobacterial abundance at different sites is similar, and the dominant cyanobacterial genus is \textit{Phormidium}. The degree of dominance by \textit{Phormidium} varies, and differences in less abundant cyanobacterial genera (e.g. \textit{Leptolyngbya} and \textit{Microcoleus}) are evident between sites. For example \textit{Microcoleus} is the second most abundant identified cyanobacterial genus, being quite abundant in dune flank (2.1 \%) and claypan (3.1 \%) but rare in nebkha (0.2 \%).

